IP - Internet Protocol
-> Address used to identify a device on the internet or local network
-> It contains location information and make devices accessible for communication

Versions of IP
IPv4
-> Original internet protocol
-> 32-bit numeric dot decimal notation 
-> Allows only 4 billion IP addresses
Example: 102.22.192.181

IPv6
-> Introduced in 1998
-> 128-bit alphanumeric hexadecimal notation
-> Can provide about ~340e+36 IP addresses
Example: 2001:0db8:85a3:0000:0000:8a2e:0370:7334

Type of IP
Public
-> One primary address is associated with whole network
-> Each connected device has same IP address
Example: IP address provided to your router by the ISP.

Private 
-> Unique IP number assigned to every device that connects with internet
Example: IP addresses generated by your home router for your devices.

Static
-> IP does not change
-> Manually created
-> More expensive but reliable
Example: They are usually used for important things like reliable geo-location services, remote access, server hosting, etc.

Dynamic
-> IP changes from time to time, not always the same 
-> Assigned by Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) server
-> Most common, cheaper to deploy, allows reuse of IP addresses within a network
Example: They are more commonly used for consumer equipment and personal use.
